    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.6.52-54_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">52</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>717 E. 2nd St., Northfield, Minn., Dec. 14, 1919.</dateline>
                
                <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:&#8212;</salute></opener> <p>I want to thank you for the great pleasure you have given me in sending me your two poems&#8212; "The Song of Hugh Glass" and "The Three Friends". I have not only read them but reread them and some parts several times. They appeal profoundly to me. Perhaps you don't know that I spent my childhood in Sweden. As a child I was brought up in the heroic background of ancient story and saga. I have always felt grateful for this background. Not only has it given me much enjoyment, but I feel that it has given 
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.6.52-54_0002"/>
                
                    me a saner perspective of life. Now you are making it possible for the American youth in beautiful poetry to make real to it-self its own heroic background. It is safe to say that if he reads your poems, he will never forget the impression. One returns with more drawing to Hugh Glass where suffering is blended with atonement. But "The Three Friends" reminds one of the terrible and inexorable tragedy of the old sagas. You are doing a great work for America and the world in thus preserving these bits of heroic past in beautiful song.
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.6.52-54_0003"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">54</fw>
                
                    I am glad to have this more intimate contact with the soul of one who has befriended me so much. I hope to see you one day and before very long.</p>
                
                <p>I am sorry not to be able to send you "Creative Religion", The book I had promised. It was to have been published by the Chicago University Press this fall, but on account of financial conditions they canceled the publication of that and other new books which were included with it on the reommendation of the Press Board. So now I have to find a new publisher. I shall not forget to <unclear>send</unclear> it when it comes out.</p> 
                <closer>
                    <salute>With many thanks and best wishes,</salute>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours, </salute>
                
                    <signed><unclear>John E. Boodin</unclear></signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
